rComments: Best professor I had ever had at utm. He actually cares about your success as a student and is more than happy to accommodate lectures or tests for personal conflicts.

Hes one of the few lecturers left at UTM that cares about his students. Yes his lectures are 100% mandatory, but if you are actively listening he repeats key concepts and puts a verbal emphasis. Hes a prof that its straight forward and testing, nothing is a surprise. Success is inevitable in his course if you put a shred of effort in.
teacherRatingTags: ['Caring', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: Overall Professor Levinsky is an okay choice for a professor. You can tell he cares about his students. With that being said, his lectures can be difficult to follow, and he gets so deep into the concepts some things really seem irrelevant. Assignments/tests are difficult, but some of them are kinda fun, such as the Courtroom Ethnography.

Apparently, Levinsky got some bad ratings recently. He is the kind of professor who will be rated outstanding by those who actually want to learn, who like to be challenged and who want to engage in critical thinking. For you it will be a walk in the park. Those who want to memorize regurgitate a textbook, do not choose his classes!

This prof, uses no text book and assigns heavy readings every week. With the mid-term and final exam, you're expected to draw inferences from the readings and provide essay-style answers. His lectures do not do a good job of indicating where to focus during readings
He okay but not clear disorganized and hard to follow at times. Nice prof if talk to after class.
Very disorganized I finded him confusing in lecture.

he's tough but worth the pain. really chill, laid back guy who's actually really fun to talk to once you take the chance. readings are everything but lectures really help clarify it all. you won't like him if you're taking the class to sleep through, he makes you work and it feels damn good when you get that a in the end.

Had class with him about 3 times and hated him at first. My last two classes with him were more successful because I learned his teaching style and what he expected. His lectures are long and sometimes did not help me, but the readings are key! He looks more for analyzing rather than summarizing readings for assignments and tests! Not easy or hard.

I would not recommend him. I am not a bitter student. I just want to warn my fellow peers in academia of Levinsky. He is not clear at all, very choppy no linear progression of his lectures. Even lectures on his own research area are terribly unclear. I constantly found myself needing to consult outside research to gain clarity on his points.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', 'Tough grader', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: He is a great professor! Focus on what he says about the readings, he explains them thoroughly and makes them relatable to real life situations. 2 test and 2 assignments, no final exam. Best structure in terms of workload and the assignments allow for creative thinking which is refreshing. Focus on what he says about the readings and youll do well.
teacherRatingTags: ['EXTRA CREDIT', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: From what I've seen, the only people that complain or do bad in his class are the people who skip a lot and are expecting an easy class. All you literally need to do is pay attention to his lectures, everything on the test is from lecture itself. Got a 90 just doing this. He's very intelligent, those who aren't won't like him.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Easily and by far the most insufferable course I took in my criminology major.  The course is called "Theories in Criminology"; however all he ever seemed to focus on was his own researchinterests (which I found boring and mostly irrelevant to the course).  I would not recommend this professor.
I hated his hat. The assignment was a huge pain.  Tests was easy - he tells you what to focus on. The exam was unnecessarily long and should not have been cumulative.

He was a great prof, the class requires effort which people don't like, it is university... For projects I put hours into them because he made them so interesting and you could throw in some personal opinion. Opposed to other Sociology profs who are 'open minded' but beware of straying from their opinion because your grade goes south.
I hate him, hate him HATE HIM!! You never really know what he's asking of you, and he makes things too complex! I'm gonna avoid him for the rest of my university career

A very thorough lecturer. He is extremely intelligent and knowledgeable in the field of criminology. He's not a textbook lecturer, thus the classes become interesting when students engage with him using course content and critical thinking. One of my favourites for sure.

Good guy. IS HELPFUL, you just have to ask. Midterm is easy if you did your readings. Essay is easy once you talk to him about how specific you thesis should be. Overall easy class IF you show up, talk to him, and do readings.
does not give guidelines for tests. during lecture, just reads off from his papers = dull and often too fast to write down. did not enjoy class

Great Prof for anyone  who is actually interested in what  they are doing. Appreciates out of the box thinking. Not recommended for kids who don't come to class and just want to memorize textbook stuff as he usually uses academic journal articles and requires critical thinking. Great Prof!

Very interesting and thinks he is super funny. Keeps class motivated and asks for class participation. Does not go over readings and does not tell you what will be on the test. Overall, a fun class and his lectures are straightforward.
